{{nihongo foot|'''''Transformers: Mystery of Convoy'''''|戦え! 超ロボット生命体トランスフォーマー コンボイの謎(ナゾ)|Tatakae! Chō Robotto Seimeitai Toransufōmā: Konboi no Nazo|lit. "Fight! Super Robot Life-Form Transformers: Mystery of Convoy"|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a 1986 video game developed by ISCO and published by [[Takara]] in Japan for the [[Famicom]]. It is based on the ''[[Transformers (toy line)|Transformers]]'' toyline.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.takaratomy.co.jp/products/gamesoft/blog/i0300/post_46.html|script-title=ja:『トランスフォーマー・コンボイの謎』でレッツトラウマ|trans-title=Let's trauma in ''Transformers: Mystery of Convoy''|date= 2008-06-06|access-date= 2009-02-27|publisher= [[Takara Tomy]]|language= ja|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120217095202/http://www.takaratomy.co.jp/products/gamesoft/blog/i0300/post_46.html|archive-date=2012-02-17 }}</ref> The game was made available on the [[Wii]]'s [[Virtual Console]] service on June 10, 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_tf/index.html|title= VC トランスフォーマー コンボイの謎|trans-title=Virtual Console - ''Transformers: Mystery of Convoy''|access-date= 2009-02-27|publisher= Nintendo|language= ja}}</ref>

The game stars [[Autobot]] protagonist [[Ultra Magnus]]. The titular ''Mystery'' is the identity of Optimus Prime's (referred to in the title as "Convoy") killer, as the [[The Transformers: The Movie|1986 film]] did not see a Japanese release for another four years.{{fact|date=December 2023}} Thus, Optimus Prime's death was not adequately explained to the Japanese audience; this game was intended to capitalize on that gap.

==Gameplay==
The player controls Ultra Magnus, who must shoot his way through 10 horizontally and vertically scrolling levels consisting of various [[Decepticon]] enemies, with a [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] fight at the end of each level. He can transform into a car carrier, which makes it easier for him to avoid enemy attacks, drive through narrow entrances and shoot enemies that are flying above him. Along the way, he can also pick up various [[power-up]]s which can give him wider ranging firepower or even the ability to fly. There are two [[Warp (video games)|Warp Zones]] within the game; they can be found by rescuing [[Bumblebee (Transformers)|Bumblebee]] from the Decepticons.

The bosses for each level consist of mostly large Decepticon symbols in different color palettes. The only Deceptions Ultra Magnus actually fights are Megatron, who for unexplained reasons is the penultimate boss, and [[Trypticon]] (known in Japan as Dinosaurer), the final boss.<ref name=1up>{{cite web |url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=1&cId=3160736 |title=Robots in Disgust |last=Oxford |first=Nadia |page=2 |date=2007-03-07 |work=[[1UP.com]] |publisher=[[IGN Entertainment]] |access-date=2014-06-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305062613/http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=1&cId=3160736 |archive-date=March 5, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>

Another playable character in the game is [[Rodimus|Rodimus Prime]], who can be unlocked by collecting the letters that spell Rodimus. One is hidden, sequentially, in levels 1, 2, 4, 5, 7, 8, and 9. However, though his vehicle mode has its own graphics, his robot-mode [[sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]] is Ultra Magnus in Rodimus's palette.

